content.short-description: "There’s a distinct man-cave vibe at Attitude, the live-music bar that’s skulking on the corner of DLF’s Supermart. It debuted as a purpose-built performance venue sometime last year, but a recent overhaul has seen it transform from a gritty neighbourhood dive to an unpretentious bachelor-pad-esque bar. Come showtime (usually on Wednesday and Saturday nights), acts like Indian Ocean and Faridkot perform on a small stage that places bands inches away from their front- row fans. The cocktail menu is brief and ideal for indecisive orderers. Not for Attitude any of that palaver of fruity concoctions and frou-frou glasses. Highlights: a frosty margarita and a long-poured Long Island iced tea, both Rs 385. It feels more in keeping with the testosterone theme to order a beer anyway, so it’s lucky that Attitude has lots of beer on their menu. Welcoming waitstaff (no attitude there) and a serious attitude towards booze and music (it’s all rock, all the time) mean two thumbs up, or at least a raised fore- and little finger, for this neighbourhood joint. "

content.description: Fashion designer Rohit Bal’s Cibo is a bit of a riddle. Some give it a hearty thumbs up, while others feel it lacks a certain something. In fact, the head-scratching begins from its location: it’s in the Janpath hotel. Not quite the venue you’d expect to be hosting a Gudda-backed hotspot, we thought. The line between restaurant and club is completely blurred here, and we had to wait a while for our drinks because of how busy the bartenders were (it was a Friday night) but once we got their attention, they were brilliant. They were spot on with a mojito (all cocktails are a flat ` 475). It had the perfect balance of alcohol, mint and sugar – one of the best we’ve had in this city. The sex on the beach was on the strong side, but the bartender threw in a bit more orange and pineapple juice and that sorted it out. Please note: the glasses (and hence the drinks) are huge. The drinks and the service are fabulous: if they’d just make up their minds about whether it’s a club or a restaurant, then it would be our go-to venue of the season - AM

Anatolia – the culinary arm of a company that trades in Turkey – is run by Turks and claims to be Delhi’s first real Turkish restaurant. Crammed between glittering sari shops is a shawarma spit behind the glass doors, manned by the portly Turkish chef with startlingly blue eyes. The restaurant is spotlessly clean with serviceable canteen-style seating and photographs of the Bosphorus and Cappadoccia. Though there are some Indian dishes, try the affordable, unpretentious foreign fare. Hummus and roomali roti, falafal, aubergine kabab and urfa kabab are some of our favourites. While we can’t judge whether Anatolia serves “authentic” Turkish food, there is something honest and earnest about this little piece of the world in Dilli’s tinsel heart. No alcohol served. Home delivery in the area and outdoor catering

This is the place to sample Indian food in an upmarket, centrally-located setting without blasting your palate. There’s plenty to tickle all kinds of tongues, and western-style plating makes ordering easier. Several main courses are offered in smaller sizes too. The “varqui” crab is a good start, an edifice of crab sandwiched between thin filo dough crisps, topped with a prawn and garnished with sprigs of chive bud, dark vinegar and scraps of chilly. The martabaan ka meat, a simple, light lamb dish which comes in a ceramic pickle jar, is already a classic. Vegetarians are well-looked after and Varq has vegetarian and non-vegetarian combination meals as well

content.short-description: Noida eatery Mandarin Trail’s weekday lunches now come in a bowl so that you can beat the lunch hour rush. The rice power lunches include pak choi and asparagus in black pepper sauce, beancurd in spicy garlic sauce, sautéed fish and prawn in black bean sauce and sliced lamb in chilly bean sauce. Noodle options range from Hunan-style wok-fried noodles with prawns to sliced fish in XO sauce and noodles with babycorn, spinach and ginger chilli sauce.

This American Tex-Mex chain has a whole host of new offerings. Sample their pimento cheese dip with tortillas, celery and pickle chips, guacamole, Asian glazed salmon served with sugar snap peas, spinach and parmesan ravioli, Santa Fe chicken salad and chicken Florentine. There are also burgers, salads and soups on offer. A special ribs-and-fajitas promo, on for the month, offers a half rack of tender barbecue ribs with sesame-peanut glazed wings, and Louisiana fried shrimp. Their fajitas are grilled with onions and bell peppers and served with soft

content.description: "The “lifestyle section” as you walk into F Bar sets the tone in no uncertain terms. The interiors are black and dimly lit. There are large tables enclosed with ropes of lights that hang down cabana-like from the high ceilings. They change colour every now and then, keeping time with the music. The bar is the pièce de résistance and acts as a sort of divider between this section and the dancefloor. F Bar doesn’t have just a VIP lounge, but a VVIP lounge (called the Diamond Room), complete with a separate entrance. The former overlooks the dance floor and is tastefully done in dark wood and shades of brown, ecru and beige. The latter permits a maximum of ten people for a price-tag of Rs one lakh, and it looks like… well, does it even matter? For the rest of us, here’s a tip: order the ronella (all cocktails are Rs 500) at the bar. It’s not on the menu, but it’s the bartender’s secret potion. And it’s delicious, with copious amounts of vodka, orange and lemon chunks and ginger syrup. The hummus and baba ghanoush (Rs 500) make excellent finger food. Pop in for an after-party as it’s open really, really late."

content.short-description: "HRC is located in Delhi’s mall strip, occupying a large space on the first floor of Saket’s DLF Place. The jocular staff manage to take the edge off your having to shell out Rs 250 as cover charge (Note: you only pay when a band is playing, usually Thursday nights.) The space opens up in front of you when you walk in, with a stage to the right. The glass-enclosed smoking room is massive, with large windows that are permanently open to allow fresh air in, making this one of the few places in Delhi where smokers are given a decent space to congregate. Naturally, there’s lots of music memorabilia (all properly labelled to show what’s what). HRC is normally packed: clearly, both rock and Hard Rock pack a punch in Delhi. There’s a hefty cocktail list and menu. The berry blush – vodka and raspberry syrup with some bay leaves floating in it (Rs 354) – was lovely."

"India’s only tiki bar, handily located on the Mehrauli-Gurgaon stretch, will help you project yourself into the Polynesian isles without having to spring for a long-distance ticket. Décor that includes tiki masks (the tribal carvings from which tiki culture gets its name) and a liquor selection that boasts more candy-coloured concoctions than Barbie’s bar cabinet mean that the island motif is never missing. At Jolly Rogers, their patrons’ inebriation is their main concern. Their appropriately rum-heavy cocktail menu abounds with drinks whose selling point is their alcoholic strength (not something to turn your nose up at), with most drinks bragging at least a trio of varying shots in their ingredients list. Tiki-bar cocktails are all about lots of fresh fruit juices and excellent rum, and Jolly Rogers scores high on both counts. The rise up (Rs 375) was a punchy grapefruit juice and spiced rum treat that rocked a pleasing spiciness. The very appropriately named taxi call (Rs 375) blended rum, Malibu and tropical-fruit juice to create a thoroughly rum do that was incredibly potent (if slightly medicinal). Say aloha to the tiki staples, icy piña coladas and mai tais, and if kitschy and saccharine theme drinks don’t tickle your fancy, mojitos and margaritas are reliable fallbacks, with sufficient island flavour to put some wind in your sails (all Rs 325). It’s luau at first sight."

"There’s too rarely a distinction between a Delhi club and a drinking hole, and that’s one reason why Marut and Anusuiya Sikka have struck gold with Keya. It’s a bar-bar: classic, elegant and supremely cosmopolitan with not one twitch of a personality disorder. The interior is dominated by a massive island bar with an ebony base and a swelling, translucent alabaster counter. It’s the perfect atmosphere to explore Keya’s creative cocktails, most of which seem to have evolved from Delhi’s street markets. The Keya magique (Rs 400) is a paan mojito, with bits of betel leaf and supari floating around the muddled vodka and a betel garnish that radiates aroma and flavour. A genuinely surprising drink – spicy and tart with explosive flavour – was the mast guava (Rs 225), a tumbler filled to the brim with guava juice, vodka, a hint of lemon juice, chilli, chaat masala and black salt. The bar snacks were equally innovative, a bit like Indian tapas. A plate of tawa-roasted lamb tikka (Rs 375) came moist, succulent and beautifully marinated. Along with the cocktails, the food will leave you shining as bright as any glowworm."

"Big enough to fit all your friends, small enough to make you feel right in the centre of things. Bar snacks in whisky glasses, “panchayats” or punches in bowls for five people. Hip new bar Red Monkey, swinging from the treetops above Chilli Seasonss, is already a big deal in a small space. A night here can be subdued (on a weeknight) or raucous (on weekends). The all-Indian wine list starts at Rs 400, and the beer selection includes Stella Artois, Corona, Hoegaarden, Budweiser and Kingfisher. The cocktail menu comes dotted with anecdotes and names; by the end of the night you’ll feel like you know the owners, all their friends and their drink preferences – who invented the vodka nimbu lemonade, who likes the Bloody Mary and why a holiday in Thailand inspired a martini recipe. That’s if they don’t come swooping down to your table in person to chat. Skip the martinis, however, for the addictive kala-namak-tinged vodka-nimbu lemonade (Rs 325). “Your grandmother’s nimbu pani” says the description, which was substantially correct – if your grandmother likes her nimbu pani crisp, salty and spiked with enough vodka to worry a Russian. On a busy night, it can even feel like a party at someone’s cramped flat. But for a watering hole to be this swinging a month into its existence is impressive. This just might be the year of the monkey. "

Shalom part deux mostly sticks with the original’s game plan; it still has that white, Mediterranean low-lit vibe. Like the Shalom of old, screens with crazy graphics play on a loop, seemingly in sync with the music. The music itself is far more progressive-ambient than in GK (for those who’re wondering, the music has lyrics). What this place really scores with are the snacks and cocktails. The caipiroska (Rs 395) was as lemony and tart as a caipiroska should be. The cosmopolitan (Rs 395), a simple drink that often goes horribly wrong, didn’t overwhelm with the booze and was refreshingly chilled. The Arabic sushi platter (Rs 595) is beautifully presented and comes with pieces of lamb, fish, chicken, cottage cheese and one roll of baba ghanoush wrapped in nori sheets. Saturdays normally are gig nights, with BLOT, BASSFoundation, Jalebee Cartel and Midival Punditz often playing, so call ahead to check. These happen in the basement which, conveniently, has its own bar.

"New Review Veda is lots of things, but subtle is not one of them. If you’ve been to Veda’s first outpost, the lounge bar and restaurant in Connaught Place that takes its stylistic cues from a Maharaja’s brothel, you’ll remember an immeasurably dramatic lounge bar. Designer and owner Rohit Bal’s second go has none of the excessive (but so enjoyable) splendour of the original. They’ve given it a good go, but Veda no. 2 still has the faintest air of Geoffrey’s-on-acid. Is this a good thing? It really depends how partial you are to Geoffrey’s. But décor aside, Veda has a fair few tricks up its nouveau-Indian sleeve: a cocktail menu divided by spirit makes browsing a doddle and yielded the excellent gin-based cucumber apple fantasy (Rs 375). Its silly name belies how well-crafted this drink is, mixing Bombay Sapphire gin with elderflower, cucumber, apple syrup and lime, and garnished with an additional massive chunk of cucumber. Zesty and crisp, with just a hint of aromatic elderflower, this is summertime in a martini glass. The orange and mint tall (Rs 425) was suitably potent, joining together vodka, rum, tequila and fresh orange into a punch and a Bellini (Rs 425) delivered on all counts, a perfectly dry and tart blend of sparkling wine and peach-and-orange purée. Mostly populated by diners, choose a table only if you plan to eat. Otherwise we’d recommend perching at the bar: an island that channels some of that old Veda vibe, with a blood-red chandelier and mood lighting. This one’s probably best reserved for lovers of tempered down brothel-chic, dinner and drinks for two, and for fancy concoctions in fancy glasses."
INTACH Delhi conducts a heritage walk through the Nizamuddin area. Highlights include a visit to the tomb of Nizamuddin Aulia and poet Mirza Ghalib.

content.description: The Blue Bar is a single irridescent room, glowing in marine blues and purples, warmed by the twinkle of golden light in the chandeliers above and the glasses behind the bar. The grey strip bar looks like it expects Danny Ocean and his eleven merry men to arrive any minute, and lean on it to trade suave dialogue. We began with the coffee and passionfruit margarita (` 650), a blend of Patrón tequila, Grand Marnier and Kahlúa (the coffee element) shaken with passionfruit and lime juice. This correspondent thought she wasn’t a fan of tequila, but the citrus bite of the fruit and the whiff of coffee were spectacular together. The Belgravia (` 450) followed, a cocktail of Tanqueray gin muddled with cucumber, fresh ginger and elderflower. We wondered whether the Mata Hari (` 650), plum-infused sake, plum compote , Hendricks gin and lime juice, could keep up the standard, and it did. Three out of three in perfect form, a rare mixological performance. We rounded up with the fig jagger (an homage to Mick; ` 450): Morgan spiced rum with fresh figs, caramel, jaggery and red chilli. It left us with what poor Mick never got, total satisfaction - Ambika Muttoo

content.description: Ink Bar sits where the erstwhile Tabula Rasa once stood. It’s much smaller than the original Tabula Rasa, and the décor is all very red-tinged, with a long crimson back-lit bar and red accents on the wall. Ink seems like the sort of space where you come in to snack and have a drink or two. The far side of the room has a sliding door that reveals a VIP room with its own bar, and blue walls lined with large divans scattered with plump cushions. We ordered a bellini (` 495) first, usually a fairly simple drink. This is what the bartender did: he put in some ice, poured in some wine, then sniffed the peach puree which looked frozen, grimaced and then threw everything out. At the end of all this, when we finally got our drink, it tasted off. We went for a Hong Kong sling next, which had Absolut vanilla vodka with lychee juice (` 425). All we could taste was the vanilla vodka. This was in a rather large glass (top marks for helpings),so all that vanilla just got cloying somewhere down the middle. We may not be enamoured by the drinks but the staff are really sweet and helpful, so we’re hoping they’ll get it right - AM

content.description: New review Lure is the newest venture to set up shop at Tavern on the Greens, that hexed site which has thus far played host to F-Bar (the original), Climax (of the cringey name) and Bar Sávanh by Indochine (who now?). So Lure has to try pretty hard from the get-go to shake off the T-on-the-G curse if it is to survive where its once-popular predecessors couldn’t. The hook here (in case your reference meter is set to zero) is sort of surreal-nautical, we think. There’s also a sort of Lado Sarai homage to surrealism, where gold-dipped furniture, a gramophone and a beatific looking stag are being sucked into the wall high above the bar. There’s a lot of outdoor space, which augurs well for nights when Lure hosts a big-name DJ or live act, because there’ll be room to mill about without getting lost in the crush (we’re talking to you, Hard Rock).The food menu careens wildly between Italian, Japanese, Chinese and Punjabi – not a fusion that inspires confidence. Neither does the cocktail menu, which waffles on for pages and pages of liquor, blended drinks and an odd little saké-and-sh2ochu interlude. Eager and enthusiastic service did not make up for a margarita (` 600) that was, at best, passable, or an irredeemable and oversweet mint julep (` 600), that was sent back and replaced with a still-too-sweet drink. To predict the fate of a bar when it’s still in its infancy feels premature, but still, our money’s on the curse of Lado Sarai - VV

content.description: Olive is all beautiful white, minimal, mood-lit ambience. A little bridge over a moat takes visitors to a semi-covered walkway replete with ivy on white rafters and lanterns. Drink to the sounds of Ella and Duke and a soundtrack of smoky jazz and the blues. It’s just loud enough to diffuse a neighbouring table’s conversation, but not enough to hinder your own tête-à-tête. Do sit by the bar and say hello to Arvind the bartender who makes a mean chocotini, which they’re encouraged to serve gratis in cute little martini glasses. Not enough can be said about this drink; it’s got Kahlúa, a touch of Bailey’s, chocolate and coffee mixed in a flawless combination. The bellini (` 500) is delicious too. The blueberry mojito and the passion fruit daiquiri (both ` 425) are when the cocktails here really prove their mettle. The rum’s there all right, but you can’t really taste it because it’s blended wonderfully with the fruit. Olive Beach is a perfect, relaxed evening out, even on normally crowded Delhi weekends - AM

content.description: At this fine-dining eatery behind Select Citywalk mall, the décor is a little schizoid, but the food is not. Chefs Mohammad Ashfaque Qureshi and Irfan Qureshi (sons of the most famous Qureshi of all, master of the biryani and ITC’s head chef, Imtiaz Qureshi), have restricted Aquum’s menu to what they know they’re good at. Kakori kababs are well-hammered into softness, Peshawari murgh tikka is marinated in creamy yoghurt, ginger-garlic and malt vinegar. Lucknowi nehari and dum gosht Lucknowi biryani make good mains. Finish with the superlative qubani ka meetha. Poached Afghani apricots dissolve delicately on the tongue amid whirls of thick malai, leaving a cinnamon and saffron aftertaste

content.description: China Club is a fairly authentic Chinese eatery, save for a few diversions in the décor and the dessert menu – and we love it just for giving the standard cheesy blue crockery a miss. Everything in this restaurant is expansive, from its sheer size to its exhaustive spirits and wines menu to the choice of dishes. Tastes are subtle, the service is timely and the background music is mostly unobtrusive. The garupa in black bean sauce is stunning.The prawns in crispy fried chilly and garlic are so light and supple a dish that you’ll be transported to a Hong Kong wharf, and the tenderloin in black pepper sauce is cooked just right. Braised bean curd with peanuts and dried chilli will make sure vegetarians don’t get the short end of the stick either

content.description: This red-and-black minimalist pigeonhole on the top floor of Select Citywalk looks like it couldn’t hold more than ten people, but it has an expansive terrace with its own bar, and own name – “Joy Luck Sky.” Mall rats will be amazed at the vista that opens before them, even if it’s only the back of Select Citywalk. The menu isn’t especially creative, but the food is a comfortable spread of Chinese dishes, with a few Thai interlopers. The vegetarian Cantonese spring rolls, which appear threaded through with chives, are comfortingly greaseless, and the spicy squid salad dresses up the normally delicate taste of calamari very well. We like the simply-flavoured black pepper sliced lamb. The crispy wine chilly fish comes in a light, spicy marinade with the barest twang of wine, and the pak choi is festooned with ornate black mushrooms. Joy Luck Moon is a great, not-too-expensive stop on the way to more shoes

content.description: If your idea of a good night out is lounging in a throwback to art deco Miami, then you may find solace in the Park Hotel’s Mist, with its sumptuous desserts, quality imported beers, Miami-style Art Deco interiors and Eames-esque chairs. This eatery’s eight-page, eclectic menu may seem hard to navigate, but the savvy diner can indulge in a delectable international meal here. A savvy chef and first-rate ingredients ensure that everything is soft and crispy in all the right places. The chicken satay is tender, glazed with cheese and chased with a perfect freshly-made peanut sauce. Mist’s pizzas are also justly famous; try the smoked salmon

content.description: In all the hype surrounding Paranthewali Gali and its deep-fried products, other parantha shrines in the old city tend to be slightly neglected. For instance there is no better-kept secret than Nirmal Restaurant, located above a cluster of tiny shops in Chandni Chowk. A short climb up the narrow, grimy staircase leads you to a spacious blue-green room full of hungry diners. The atmosphere is as old-world as it gets, and the paneer paranthas, made by the third-generation descendants of the original owner, Asha Ram, are richly stuffed. Just like you’ll be

This quiet restaurant is tucked away in Jorbagh’s sleepy main market, a few doors down from The Steakhouse. Purana Villa’s menu is mostly tandoori and North Indian, but don’t skip the “Mangalorean delicacies” section. Nilgiri tangri kababs are char-grilled, succulent chicken drumsticks, rudimentary but toothsome and well-spiced, and the surmai tawa masala is heavy but dhania-marinated and delicious. The prawn ghassi comprises large, splendidly soft prawns, curled up in a rich, heavy gravy of coconut milk, curry leaf and spices

content.description: Pink Hello Kitty flower chandeliers bloom from the ceilings of the upbeat, stylish fine-dining area, café and grill (with India’s first sushi conveyor belt), outdoor terrace and backroom bar. The fun is buoyed by honest, tasty fare, inspired by China, but taking in other eastern and even western influences.The dim sum stands out (try the crispy duck spring rolls served piping hot with a gooseberry sauce, the barbecue pork bao or the Shanghai chicken dumplings). The desserts from the dedicated pastry kitchen are stellar (we’ve tried all of them). They’ve got great lunchtime sushi deals, so trundle along

content.description: Nature’s Basket may be the shop du jour on this Defence Colony road, but neighbouring Moon River won’t give up so easily. The interior-design store has just opened a pretty little tea shop at the back. The space is sunny and airy, and as befits a café inside a home décor shop, decked out with wonderfully comfortable rattan chairs and tables, big bookshelves, artwork by Gond artist Durga Bai, tall leafy plants and cane-twined lamps. The bookshelves lining the far end are populated with books you actually want to pick up (from Nigella Bites to David Mitchell’s The Thousand Autumns of Jacob de Zoet) and there are entire shelves spilling over with design mags, volumes of Wallpaper* and international Time Outs. It all has the air of someone’s (very well-designed) living room: just messy enough to be friendly, just sleek enough to make you lust for their white-cushioned furniture.Tea and coffee come in glass-and-steel pots on red and black lacquered trays. The menu includes cakes, muffins and whole-wheat pizzas. The chocolate cake (` 150) is a huge fudgey doorstop which may require two to plough through it. More manageable are the muffins (dark chocolate and lemon-infused vanilla, ` 90), which go excellently with Moon River’s demitasse cups of Lavazza coffee (` 65). But the best thing here is the selection of teas, which runs from flowering jasmine-lotus and milk oolong to camomile and berry (from ` 60). Tucked away behind Moon River’s swirly glass vases and etched terracotta platters, this is a tranquil place to unwind. The big tables and cushioned chairs are great for conversation, but the iPod in the corner has an eclectic playlist to help you drift away in a Holly Golightly moment - NMO

content.description: This eatery’s seedy location doesn’t do much to recommend it, but their food will. The menu concentrates on well-executed crowd-pleasers – apricot koftas, seekh pasanda, murg parcha kabab.
All the glitter a Delhi Punjabi’s heart could desire can be found in the central chandelier alone. The excellent Punjabi food is backed by Jiggs Kalra’s decades of research and experience

content.description: A small kitchen just behind Uday Park dishing out Kashmiri wazwan fare. Takeaway only, with no seating, and you’ll need to order in advance.
The last great kabab bastion before you hit Gurgaon, Al-Kauser displays a remarkable consistency across a variety of kababs – and serves a mean nihari as well. Outdoor seating and lightning-fast.
“If you like, tell others, if you don’t, tell us,” the menu says. Well, we’re telling you. Run by a family from Matia Mahal, Purani Dilli’s chicken changezi, biryani and haleem are reliably good.
Babu Bhai in person is Mohammad Shakir, who capably mans his father’s kabab grill in this shuttered hole-in-the-ground in Chitli Qabar. Only one or two kinds of kababs are on offer.
One of the market’s institutions, Gulati’s menu is a Pandara’s box of Mughlai-tandoori classics. Focus on their rich chicken and mutton offerings
